  <thing id="rAngelou" name="Angelounian" description="+2 to Bluff, Concentration, and Spellcraft checks\n\n{b}General Info{/b}: The angelounians are an old race, though weak of body each is strong of mind and possesses an innate ability for prophecy. It is both a gift and a curse, for no matter how they try, they cannot change what must be. Still, thier culture is one that emphasises both stoicism and serenity, so they bear the burden well.\n\n{b}Personality{/b}: Most angelounians are serious and reserved, keeping secrets close, but offering counsel to those who they trusts. They often puzzle those around them by acting on future information, and this makes those around them nervous. Above all, they must struggle to relate to the world as seen by those firmly rooted in the present, or else be shunned as alien by all.\n\n{b}Physical Description{/b}: Modern angelounians bear little resemblance to the Ancients of legend (see Mask Dependant). They are about the same height as humans, though many suffer from twisted spines, resulting in a permanent stoop. Other common afflictions are scaly black scabs, weeping sores, and jaundiced, leathery skin. They are also significantly more slight than the human norm, with long, wasted limbs that somehow still possess a modicum of their ancestor&apos;s grace. Clothing is frequently baggy and always chosen for maximum coverage, with hooded robes of various styles being the norm. The face is concealed by a glamered mask that can change it&apos;s appearance, and any other exposed flesh, such as the hands, is tightly wrapped in linen strips.\n\nIf one can get through the mask and layers of clothing, they will notice angelounian eye color varies but is always an intense shade. Commonly seen are red (light pink to bloody crimson), blue (aqua to sapphire) or green (yellow-green to darkest emerald). Hair comes in all the same colors as the common races, but is frequently patchy and hidden away under a hood. Niether males nor females are known to grow facial hair.\n\n{b}Alignment{/b}: Angelounian culture teaches the ways of Kael (that which must be) and emphasises discipline of mind to meet the future without flinching. Most willingly follow the paths of destiny and fulfill their roles in the Kael, but some few reject this and seek to alter some future fate. Whether motivated by selfish (determined to escape a grim fate) or altruistic (seeking to avert some terrible disaster) reasons, these are among the most desperate and dangerous individuals in the world.\n\nAngelounians tend strongly toward Lawful alignments, and are generally good or nuetral.\n\n{b}Religion{/b}: Angelounians believe first and foremost in Kael. Beyond that, the dualistic philosophy of Len&apos;thi (the mind, a force of discipline) and Dao&apos;len (the physical, a force of chaotic instinct) which roughly translates to Light and Shadow, provides daily instruction. Magic is the imposition of the Len&apos;thi through Kael to forge a change in Dao&apos;len. It requires intense discipline and is considered the highest art.\n\nThough they acknowledge both their existance and power, angelounians do not generally worship the gods. To thier way of thinking, all things have thier parts to play in the Kael, from the mightiest gods to the lowliest ant, and power does not entitle one to worship.\n\n{b}Language{/b}: Much like druidic, Angelounian remains a secret language, imbued in each member of the race upon creation and not taught to others.\n\nAngelounian words consist of syllables of 2, 3, or occasionally 4 letters for particularly powerful words. The second letter of a syllable must be a vowel, unless it is replaced by a soft h, in which it can be pushed forward or back one space, such as in &quot;thi&quot; or ahn. When vowels are paired, the second is modified to say its name, unless they are the first two letters of a word (in which case the first is emphasised). There are few &quot;powerful&quot; sounds such as a hard &quot;k&quot;, which is often replaced by &quot;q&quot; of softer intonation. Syllables are seperated by &apos; which indicates a slight pause when speaking, and words are seperated by spaces, which are longer pauses. \n\n{b}Names{/b}: There is no distinction between male and female names among angelounians. Both have a name of two syllables that they choose upon their birth and never change. There is no such thing as a &quot;family&quot; name, but a third, variable syllable is often added to the end as an honorific to denote position and power. For example, Farseers are often called &quot;Fea&quot;.\n\nCommon examples include: Fai&apos;lon, Lun&apos;ea, Ahn&apos;fe, Hin&apos;sal, Ean&apos;qol, Sha&apos;yan" compset="Race">
    <comment/>
